<paragraph blockId="8.[133,1155,782,990]" pageId="8" pageNumber="19">
Diagnosis (male). In 
<bibRefCitation author="SCHMITZ H." box="[429,615,782,806]" pageId="8" pageNumber="19" pagination="417 - 464" refId="ref7495" refString="SCHMITZ H. 1957. Phoridae. In: LINDNER E. (ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Regio n 4 (33), (Lief. 196): 417 - 464. Stuttgart, E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung." type="book chapter" year="1957">Schmitz’s (1957)</bibRefCitation>
key to Abteilung II species it runs to couplets 20 and 21 on page 432. 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz" authorityName="Schmitz" authorityYear="1948" box="[368,581,812,836]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intonsa">
<emphasis box="[368,484,813,836]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="19">M. intonsa</emphasis>
Schmitz
</taxonomicName>
is immediately distinguished by its lack of hairs on segments 3 and 4 of the abdominal venter and its costal index being clearly less than 0.5. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Becker)" baseAuthorityName="Becker" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[133,356,874,898]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palmeni">
<emphasis box="[133,255,874,898]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="19">M. palmeni</emphasis>
(Becker)
</taxonomicName>
also lacks hairs on segments 3 and 4 of the venter and has fewer bristles on the epandrium. The other three species are readily distinguished by their very different hypopygia. In the key to British species (
<bibRefCitation author="DISNEY R. H. L." box="[619,765,935,960]" pageId="8" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7257" refString="DISNEY R. H. L. 1989. Scuttle Flies Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8): 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 55, lead 1 to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Becker" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[133,255,966,990]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palmeni">
<emphasis box="[133,255,966,990]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="19">M. palmeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
